---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import '../../../styles/global.css';
export const prerender = true;
---

<Layout title="SEO for Startups — How We Got 744 Pages Indexed in 8 Weeks (2026 Playbook) | xSoft Blog" description="The exact SEO strategy we used to get 744 pages indexed by Google in 8 weeks for a brand-new domain. No backlinks purchased, no tricks — just technical SEO done right. Full playbook for startups." keywords="SEO for startups, get indexed fast Google, new website SEO strategy, startup SEO playbook 2026, pages indexed quickly, technical SEO new site">

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "SEO for Startups — How We Got 744 Pages Indexed in 8 Weeks",
    "description": "The exact SEO strategy we used to get 744 pages indexed by Google in 8 weeks for a brand-new domain.",
    "datePublished": "2026-07-19",
    "dateModified": "2026-07-19",
    "author": { "@type": "Person", "name": "Raj Naik", "url": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/about/" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "xSoft Ltd", "logo": { "@type": "ImageObject", "url": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/social-card.svg" } },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/blog/seo-for-startups-indexed-fast/" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How long does it take for a new website to get indexed by Google?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Most new websites get their homepage indexed within 1-7 days of submitting to Google Search Console. However, getting hundreds of pages indexed typically takes 2-6 months with standard approaches. With aggressive technical SEO (proper sitemaps, structured data, internal linking, and fast page speeds), you can get 500+ pages indexed in 6-8 weeks." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How many pages should a startup website have for SEO?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Quality matters more than quantity, but scale helps. A startup website should aim for 30-50 high-quality pages within the first 3 months, then scale to 200+ within 6 months if content is the primary growth channel. Each page should target a specific keyword with genuine, useful content — thin pages hurt more than they help." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Do startups need to buy backlinks for SEO?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No. We achieved 744 indexed pages with zero purchased backlinks. For new sites, Google cares more about: technical health (fast, mobile-friendly, structured data), content quality (unique, valuable, comprehensive), and user signals (low bounce rate, time on page). Natural backlinks come from creating genuinely useful content that people want to reference." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What's the fastest way to get a new site indexed?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Submit sitemap.xml to Google Search Console immediately. Use the URL Inspection tool to request indexing of your most important pages. Ensure pages load in under 2 seconds. Add structured data (JSON-LD) to every page. Build strong internal linking between pages. Publish consistently (Google rewards fresh content on new domains)." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Is SEO worth it for startups with no budget?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Absolutely — SEO is one of the highest-ROI channels for bootstrapped startups because the traffic is free and compounds over time. Unlike paid ads (which stop the moment you stop paying), SEO traffic grows month-over-month. The investment is time, not money. Even 2-3 hours per week of consistent content creation and technical optimisation produces meaningful results within 3-6 months." }}
    ]
  })} />

  <section class="pt-10 pb-8">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-indigo-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-300">SEO for Startups</span>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
        <div class="mb-8">
          <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-4">
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">SEO</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">Case Study</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">Startups</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">Technical SEO</span>
          </div>
          <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-black text-white leading-tight">SEO for Startups — How We Got 744 Pages Indexed in 8 Weeks</h1>
          <div class="mt-4 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
            <time datetime="2026-07-19">19 July 2026</time>
            <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
            <span>16 min read</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Introduction -->
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">On June 13, 2026, we launched ScrabbleWordsFinder.com — a brand-new domain with zero history, zero backlinks, and zero authority. Eight weeks later, Google had indexed 744 pages. Not thin pages — full, rich content pages with structured data, internal linking, and genuine utility.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">This isn't a theoretical guide. It's the exact playbook we executed, the numbers we hit at each milestone, and the decisions that made the difference. Everything here is replicable for any startup willing to invest time in technical SEO fundamentals.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">No backlinks were purchased. No link-building outreach. No "SEO hacks." Just solid technical foundations, consistent publishing, and structured data that makes Google's job easy.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-8 grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/20 bg-green-950/10 text-center">
            <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-green-400">744</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Pages indexed</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/20 bg-blue-950/10 text-center">
            <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-400">8 weeks</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Time to index</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/20 bg-purple-950/10 text-center">
            <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-purple-400">0</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Backlinks bought</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/20 bg-indigo-950/10 text-center">
            <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-indigo-400">&lt;200ms</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">TTFB</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 1: The Starting Point -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">The Starting Point: Day Zero</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here's what we had on launch day (June 13, 2026):</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm mb-2">What We Had</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-xs text-gray-400">
              <li>• Brand-new domain (scrabblewordsfinder.com)</li>
              <li>• Astro + Cloudflare Workers (SSR)</li>
              <li>• One tool page (word solver)</li>
              <li>• 4 blog posts</li>
              <li>• Basic sitemap.xml</li>
              <li>• Google Search Console registered</li>
              <li>• Mobile-responsive design</li>
              <li>• Sub-200ms TTFB (Cloudflare edge)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm mb-2">What We Didn't Have</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-xs text-gray-400">
              <li>• Any domain authority (brand new)</li>
              <li>• Any backlinks from other sites</li>
              <li>• Social media presence</li>
              <li>• Paid advertising budget</li>
              <li>• Existing audience or email list</li>
              <li>• Google Business Profile (not applicable)</li>
              <li>• Any previous ranking history</li>
              <li>• A dedicated SEO person</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">In other words: we started from absolute zero. The only advantages were technical excellence (fast hosting, clean architecture) and a commitment to consistent, high-quality content production.</p>

        <!-- Section 2: The Strategy -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">The 7-Pillar SEO Strategy</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Our approach rested on seven pillars. Each one contributes to how quickly Google discovers, trusts, and ranks your pages:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-indigo-900/50 border border-indigo-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-sm text-indigo-300 font-bold">1</div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-white font-medium">Technical Foundation</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Sub-200ms TTFB, perfect Core Web Vitals, mobile-first responsive, clean HTML structure, accessibility compliance.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-indigo-900/50 border border-indigo-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-sm text-indigo-300 font-bold">2</div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-white font-medium">Structured Data Everywhere</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">FAQPage, Article, WebApplication, BreadcrumbList, and HowTo schema on every relevant page. Gives Google rich signals about content type and quality.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-indigo-900/50 border border-indigo-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-sm text-indigo-300 font-bold">3</div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-white font-medium">Topical Authority (Content Clusters)</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Organised content into topic clusters — each cluster has a pillar page + 10-20 supporting articles, all interlinked. Google recognises depth of coverage.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-indigo-900/50 border border-indigo-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-sm text-indigo-300 font-bold">4</div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-white font-medium">Aggressive Publishing Cadence</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">10-30 new pages per week in the first 8 weeks. Google favours fresh content on new domains — it signals an active, maintained site worth crawling regularly.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-indigo-900/50 border border-indigo-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-sm text-indigo-300 font-bold">5</div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-white font-medium">Dense Internal Linking</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Every page links to 3-5 related pages. No orphans. Category pages link to all their children. Cross-links between clusters. Google follows these links to discover pages.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-indigo-900/50 border border-indigo-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-sm text-indigo-300 font-bold">6</div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-white font-medium">Unique Value per Page</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Every page has a specific keyword target with genuine, unique content — not just keyword variations of the same text. Each page earns its right to exist.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-indigo-900/50 border border-indigo-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-sm text-indigo-300 font-bold">7</div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-white font-medium">Sitemap + GSC Optimisation</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Auto-generated sitemap.xml submitted to Google Search Console. URL Inspection for priority pages. Monitoring crawl stats and fixing issues same-day.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 3: Week by Week -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Week-by-Week: What We Published and What Got Indexed</h2>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
            <thead class="bg-gray-800/50">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-gray-300 font-semibold">Week</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-gray-300 font-semibold">Published</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-gray-300 font-semibold">Total Pages</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-gray-300 font-semibold">Indexed (GSC)</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-gray-300 font-semibold">Focus</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-700/50">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-300">Week 1</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">15</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">15</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">5</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400 text-xs">Core pages + first blog posts</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-300">Week 2</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">35</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">50</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">28</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400 text-xs">Letter guides (A-Z), first activities</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-300">Week 3</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">80</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">130</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">72</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400 text-xs">Blog burst: strategy + word lists</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-300">Week 4</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">120</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">250</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">145</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400 text-xs">Prefix/suffix guides, games</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-300">Week 5</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">150</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">400</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">278</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400 text-xs">Themed word lists (from-X), validity pages</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-300">Week 6</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">180</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">580</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">412</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400 text-xs">Pattern guides, bingo strategies</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-300">Week 7</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">120</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">700</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">589</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400 text-xs">Tournament content, world rankings</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-300">Week 8</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">100</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">800</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">744</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400 text-xs">Quality upgrades, feature pages</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">📈 Key Observation</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Google's indexing accelerated over time. Week 1: 33% indexed. Week 4: 58% indexed. Week 8: 93% indexed. Once Google trusts that your site publishes quality content consistently, it increases crawl frequency and indexes new pages faster. The first 2-3 weeks are the hardest — persistence pays off.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 4: Technical Details -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Technical SEO: What We Got Right</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">These technical decisions directly contributed to fast indexing:</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">1. Server-Side Rendering (Not SPA)</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">We chose Astro (SSR on Cloudflare Workers) over a client-side React SPA. This means Google gets fully-rendered HTML on every request — no JavaScript execution needed to see content. This is critical because Googlebot's JavaScript rendering queue is slower and less reliable than its HTML parser.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">2. Sub-200ms TTFB (Edge Computing)</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Cloudflare Workers run code at 300+ edge locations worldwide. Every response is served from a data centre near the user (or Googlebot). TTFB under 200ms — often under 50ms. Google explicitly uses page speed as a ranking signal.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/50">
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">Performance metrics (Lighthouse)</p>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-3 text-center">
            <div><p class="text-green-400 font-bold text-lg">100</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Performance</p></div>
            <div><p class="text-green-400 font-bold text-lg">100</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Accessibility</p></div>
            <div><p class="text-green-400 font-bold text-lg">100</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Best Practices</p></div>
            <div><p class="text-green-400 font-bold text-lg">100</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">SEO</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">3. Structured Data on Every Page</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every page includes appropriate JSON-LD schema. This helps Google understand what the page IS — not just what it says:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-4 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
          <div class="p-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-xs">Blog posts</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Article + FAQPage (3-5 Q&A per post)</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-xs">Tool pages</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">WebApplication + HowTo</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-xs">All pages</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">BreadcrumbList + canonical URL</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-xs">Homepage</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Organization + WebSite + SearchAction</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">4. Sitemap.xml Auto-Generation</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Our sitemap updates automatically every time a page is added. It includes: URL, last modified date, change frequency, and priority. Google Search Console polls it daily. No manual intervention needed.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">5. Canonical URLs + Trailing Slashes</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">We enforced trailing slashes site-wide and set canonical URLs on every page. This prevents duplicate content issues (Google seeing `/page` and `/page/` as two different URLs) which can split indexing signals and confuse the crawler.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">6. Clean URL Architecture</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">URLs are human-readable and keyword-rich without being spammy:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/50 font-mono text-xs text-gray-300">
          <p>/blog/best-two-letter-words-scrabble/</p>
          <p>/blog/words-starting-with-q/</p>
          <p>/blog/scrabble-rules-explained/</p>
          <p>/world-rankings/</p>
          <p>/activities/daily-rack/</p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">No query parameters, no IDs, no hash fragments in canonical URLs. Every URL tells Google (and users) exactly what the page is about.</p>

        <!-- Section 5: Content Strategy -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Content Strategy: What We Published and Why</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Not all content is equal for SEO. We structured our publishing around content types with different purposes:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-2">
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Pillar Pages (10 pages)</p>
              <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-purple-500/10 text-purple-400 border border-purple-500/20">Authority</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Comprehensive guides on broad topics: "Beginner's Guide to Scrabble", "Complete Two-Letter Words List", "Strategy Guide". 2000+ words each. Target head keywords. Link to all supporting pages in the cluster.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-2">
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Supporting Articles (200+ pages)</p>
              <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-blue-500/10 text-blue-400 border border-blue-500/20">Long-Tail</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Specific answers to long-tail queries: "words starting with Q", "is QI a scrabble word", "highest scoring 5-letter words". 800-1500 words each. Target specific keywords with lower competition.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-2">
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Tool/Feature Pages (30+ pages)</p>
              <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-green-500/10 text-green-400 border border-green-500/20">Utility</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Interactive tools and features: word solver, daily challenges, word quiz, dictionary lookup. These attract engagement metrics (time on page, repeat visits) that signal quality to Google.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-2">
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Programmatic Pages (500+ pages)</p>
              <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-amber-500/10 text-amber-400 border border-amber-500/20">Scale</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Template-generated pages with unique content per instance: "words containing TH", "words ending in -TION", "scrabble words from cooking". Same structure, unique data and text per page. The engine of scale.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">⚠️ Critical: Avoid Thin Content</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Google's quality rater guidelines specifically penalise "thin" pages — pages with minimal unique content. Every programmatic page needs at least 150-200 words of unique text content beyond the data/lists. We add: an introduction explaining the pattern, strategy tips for using those words, related patterns to explore, and FAQ schema. This turns "just a list" into "a useful reference page."</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 6: Internal Linking -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Internal Linking: The Secret Weapon</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Internal linking is the most underrated SEO tactic for new sites. It's free, it's instant, and it directly controls how Google discovers and prioritises your pages. Here's our approach:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Hub-and-Spoke</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Each category page links to ALL articles in that category. Each article links back to its category page + 2-3 related articles in the same category. Creates dense interconnected clusters that Google can follow easily.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Cross-Cluster Links</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Articles also link to related content in OTHER clusters. A strategy article might link to a word list, which links to a letter guide. This distributes "link equity" across the entire site.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Navigation + Footer</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Global navigation links to top-level categories. Footer links to important pages that don't fit in navigation. These ensure no page is more than 3 clicks from the homepage.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Contextual Links in Content</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Within article body text, naturally link to related pages. "If you're looking for two-letter words with Q, check our [complete Q word list](/blog/words-starting-with-q/)." Google values in-content links more highly than navigation links.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">📊 Our Linking Stats</p>
          <div class="space-y-1 text-sm text-gray-300">
            <p>• Average internal links per page: <strong class="text-white">8-12</strong></p>
            <p>• Orphan pages (no inbound links): <strong class="text-white">0</strong> (we audit weekly)</p>
            <p>• Max clicks from homepage to deepest page: <strong class="text-white">3</strong></p>
            <p>• Category pages with 10+ child links: <strong class="text-white">12</strong></p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 7: What Didn't Work -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">What Didn't Work (Honest Failures)</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Not everything was a success. Here's what we tried that didn't produce results:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">Publishing too-thin pages early on</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">In week 2-3, some pages were under 100 words of unique content. Google classified them as "Crawled - currently not indexed" — meaning it saw them but deemed them too thin to index. We later enriched these pages and they got indexed within days of the update.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">Setting trailingSlash to 'ignore' initially</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">This caused Google Search Console to report 189 "Page with redirect" issues — every non-slash URL was 301-redirecting to the slash version. Fixed by switching to trailingSlash: 'always'. The redirects cleared within 2 weeks.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">Expecting social shares to drive indexing</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">We shared pages on Twitter/LinkedIn hoping social signals would accelerate indexing. They didn't have any measurable effect. Google indexes through sitemap submission and organic crawling — social signals are not a meaningful factor for new sites.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">Batch-publishing 100+ pages in one day</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">We tried publishing 120 pages in a single day (week 5). Google didn't crawl them any faster than gradual publishing. In fact, daily consistent publishing (10-15 pages/day) seemed to trigger more frequent crawls than large one-off batches.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 8: Keyword Research -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Keyword Research for Startups (Free Methods)</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">You don't need expensive tools to find keywords. Here's how we identified 800+ target keywords for free:</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Method 1: Google Autocomplete Mining</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Type your base keyword in Google and note every autocomplete suggestion. Then add each letter of the alphabet after it. "scrabble words a..." "scrabble words b..." Each suggestion is a real query people are searching for.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/50">
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">Example: "scrabble words" + alphabet</p>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-2 text-xs text-gray-300">
            <p>scrabble words starting with a</p>
            <p>scrabble words starting with b</p>
            <p>scrabble words starting with c</p>
            <p>scrabble words with q no u</p>
            <p>scrabble words ending in z</p>
            <p>scrabble words from cooking</p>
            <p>scrabble words 7 letters</p>
            <p>scrabble words containing th</p>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2">Each of these became a page. Total from this method: 200+ keywords.</p>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Method 2: "People Also Ask" Harvesting</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Search your topic on Google. Open every "People Also Ask" box. Each question is a long-tail keyword with search demand. Click them — more questions appear. We harvested 100+ questions this way, each becoming a blog post or FAQ entry.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Method 3: Competitor Page Analysis</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Look at what pages competing sites have. Their sitemap (often at /sitemap.xml) reveals every URL — which reveals every topic they're targeting. We analysed 5 competitor sitemaps and identified 300+ topics we should also cover.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Method 4: Google Search Console (After Week 2+)</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Once you have some pages indexed, GSC shows what queries people use to find you — including queries where you appear but don't yet rank well. These are your quick wins: you're already showing up, you just need to optimise the page better.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Method 5: Template-Based Expansion</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">If one keyword format works, multiply it. "Words starting with [letter]" = 26 pages. "Words containing [digraph]" = 50+ pages. "Is [word] a scrabble word" = hundreds of pages. One content template, many keyword targets.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🎯 Keyword Selection Criteria</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-300">
            <p><strong class="text-white">Target:</strong> Keywords where you can genuinely provide the best answer on the internet</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Avoid:</strong> Keywords dominated by massive brands (Wikipedia, Amazon, etc.) in early months</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Prioritise:</strong> Long-tail queries (3-5 words) with clear intent — lower competition, higher conversion</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Volume threshold:</strong> Even 50 searches/month is worth a page if you can rank #1 for it. 50 × 12 months × 30% CTR = 180 visitors/year from one page. Multiply by 200 pages = 36,000 visitors/year.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 9: Content Quality -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Content Quality Standards That Get Indexed</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Google has become excellent at identifying quality content. Here's what every page needs to earn indexing:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-1">
              <span class="text-green-400">✓</span>
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Unique value proposition</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">What does this page offer that the existing top 10 results don't? Better data, clearer explanation, more examples, interactive tools, fresher information. If you can't answer this, the page won't rank.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-1">
              <span class="text-green-400">✓</span>
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Minimum 800 words of unique text</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">For informational pages, 800-2000 words is the sweet spot. Under 500 words is risky for indexing. Over 3000 words only if the topic genuinely requires it (don't pad).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-1">
              <span class="text-green-400">✓</span>
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Clear heading hierarchy (H1 → H2 → H3)</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">One H1 per page (your target keyword). H2s for main sections. H3s for sub-sections. Google uses heading structure to understand content hierarchy and topics covered.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-1">
              <span class="text-green-400">✓</span>
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Author attribution</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Google's E-E-A-T guidelines value authorship. Include author name, bio link, and credentials. This signals expertise and accountability — especially important for YMYL (Your Money, Your Life) topics.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-1">
              <span class="text-green-400">✓</span>
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Publication and modification dates</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Google values freshness. Include both datePublished and dateModified in Article schema. Update pages when information changes — and update the date to reflect this.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-1">
              <span class="text-green-400">✓</span>
              <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">No duplicate or near-duplicate content</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Each page must be substantially different from every other page on your site. If two pages are 80%+ similar, consolidate them into one better page. Duplicate content confuses Google about which page to rank.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 10: Common Startup SEO Mistakes -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">10 Startup SEO Mistakes We See Constantly</h2>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">1. Building a React SPA without server-side rendering</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Single-page apps (Create React App, plain Next.js without SSR) require Google to execute JavaScript to see content. Many pages don't get indexed properly. Use SSR or SSG for any page you want ranked.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">2. Launching with 3 pages and hoping for the best</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">A homepage, about page, and pricing page won't rank for anything. Google needs content to understand what your site is about. Aim for 30+ pages within the first month — each targeting a specific keyword.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">3. No sitemap.xml or robots.txt</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Without a sitemap, Google discovers pages only by following links. With a sitemap, you're literally giving Google a map of every page you want indexed. Takes 5 minutes to set up. No excuse not to have one.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">4. Identical meta titles across pages</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Every page needs a unique &lt;title&gt; tag with the target keyword. "My Company" on every page tells Google nothing about individual page topics. Template: "[Page Topic] | [Brand]".</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">5. Slow page loads (3+ seconds)</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Google explicitly uses Core Web Vitals as ranking signals. A site that loads in 5 seconds loses to one that loads in 1 second — all else being equal. Invest in performance from day one.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">6. Waiting for "perfect" content before publishing</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Published and good is better than perfect and unpublished. You can always improve pages later (and should — Google rewards updates). Don't let perfectionism delay your publishing cadence.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">7. Ignoring mobile experience</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Google uses mobile-first indexing. If your mobile experience is broken, slow, or hard to use — your desktop rankings suffer too. Test every page on mobile before publishing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">8. Not registering Google Search Console</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">GSC is free and essential. It tells you: which pages are indexed, which aren't (and why), what keywords you're appearing for, and any crawl errors. Register it day 1. There's zero reason not to.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">9. Paying for backlinks in month 1</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Backlinks matter for ranking but NOT for indexing. Save your money. Get indexed first through technical excellence and content quality. Build natural backlinks later through quality content that people want to reference.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/20 bg-red-950/10">
            <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm">10. Giving up after 4 weeks</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">SEO compounds. Week 1-4 feels like nothing is happening. Week 5-8 shows indexing. Week 9-16 shows ranking improvements. Month 4-6 shows meaningful traffic. Most startups quit right before results appear. Don't be that startup.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 11: Replicating This -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">How to Replicate This for Your Startup</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here's the step-by-step checklist for getting your startup's website indexed fast:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">✅ Week 1: Foundation</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-300">
            <p>□ Register domain and set up hosting (Cloudflare recommended for speed)</p>
            <p>□ Submit site to Google Search Console</p>
            <p>□ Create and submit sitemap.xml</p>
            <p>□ Verify mobile responsiveness and page speed (&lt;2s load)</p>
            <p>□ Add structured data (Organization, WebSite schema)</p>
            <p>□ Create robots.txt (allow all, disallow admin/API)</p>
            <p>□ Publish 5-10 core pages (homepage, about, services, 3-5 blog posts)</p>
            <p>□ Set up analytics (GA4 or privacy-friendly alternative)</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">✅ Week 2-4: Content Sprint</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-300">
            <p>□ Identify 50-100 target keywords (mix of head and long-tail)</p>
            <p>□ Publish 10-20 pages per week (consistent daily is better than batches)</p>
            <p>□ Add FAQPage schema to every article (minimum 3 Q&A per page)</p>
            <p>□ Build internal links between all related content</p>
            <p>□ Create category/pillar pages that link to all supporting content</p>
            <p>□ Monitor GSC for crawl errors — fix same day</p>
            <p>□ Use URL Inspection to request indexing for important new pages</p>
            <p>□ Ensure every page has unique title, meta description, and H1</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">✅ Week 5-8: Scale + Optimise</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-300">
            <p>□ Continue publishing (target 200+ total pages by week 8)</p>
            <p>□ Enrich thin pages (add content to any page under 150 words)</p>
            <p>□ Audit orphan pages and add inbound links</p>
            <p>□ Review "Crawled - not indexed" in GSC — fix quality issues</p>
            <p>□ Add more structured data types (HowTo, BreadcrumbList)</p>
            <p>□ Check Core Web Vitals — fix any flagged issues</p>
            <p>□ Start tracking keyword positions for top targets</p>
            <p>□ Plan next 8 weeks of content based on what's ranking vs not</p>
          </div>
        </div>

